{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569396"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:27:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:27:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22102"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22102"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.1,0.06,0.33,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15063"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106622"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15063"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22102"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89099"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2240"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9736"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"39397"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39660"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43758"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106622"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review of her chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. She has a three-month history of worsening breathlessness on minimal exertion and fatigue. She has a medical history of severe COPD diagnosed eight years ago and hypertension. Her regular medications include tiotropium, salmeterol/fluticasone combination inhaler, and amlodipine. She is an ex-smoker with a 45 pack-year history, having quit five years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears comfortable at rest with a pulse rate of 92/min, blood pressure 135/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals reduced air entry bilaterally with wheeze and prolonged expiration. There is peripheral oedema to the ankles and elevated jugular venous pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArterial blood gas analysis on room air shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.38 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaCO2 52 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaO2 52 mmHg (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3- 30 mmol/L (22-26).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management regarding oxygen therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prescribe oxygen for use during sleep only","Defer oxygen therapy until PaO2 falls below 45 mmHg","Prescribe oxygen for use during exercise only","Prescribe oxygen as needed for breathlessness","Prescribe long-term oxygen therapy for at least 15 hours daily"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has severe COPD with chronic hypoxaemia and evidence of right heart failure (peripheral oedema, elevated jugular venous pressure). The arterial blood gas shows PaO2 of 52 mmHg, which meets the criteria for long-term oxygen therapy in COPD. Long-term oxygen therapy has been shown to improve survival and quality of life in patients with COPD and severe hypoxaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong-term oxygen therapy for at least 15 hours daily\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated when arterial PaO2 is \u226455 mmHg, or \u226459 mmHg in the presence of complications such as pulmonary hypertension, right heart failure, or polycythaemia. This patient\u0027s PaO2 of 52 mmHg clearly meets the first criterion. The therapy must be used for at least 15 hours per day to confer survival benefit, with greater benefit seen with continuous use. Initial oxygen prescription typically starts at 1-2 L/min via nasal prongs, with the flow rate titrated to achieve a target SpO2 of 88-92% or PaO2 \u226560 mmHg. The oxygen flow rate should be reassessed during sleep, exercise, and at rest, as requirements may vary. For patients with hypercapnia (like this patient with PaCO2 52 mmHg), careful monitoring is essential - arterial blood gases should be rechecked 30-60 minutes after initiating oxygen and again at four to six weeks to ensure CO2 retention has not worsened.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygen for exercise only\u003C/strong\u003E may help with exercise tolerance but does not provide the survival benefit that continuous long-term oxygen therapy offers. Exercise oxygen is considered separately from long-term oxygen therapy and would not address this patient\u0027s severe resting hypoxaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygen during sleep only\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient for this patient who has severe daytime hypoxaemia. Nocturnal oxygen alone does not meet the evidence-based criteria for improving survival in COPD patients with this degree of hypoxaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygen as needed for breathlessness\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for patients meeting criteria for long-term oxygen therapy. Intermittent use does not provide the physiological benefits of continuous oxygen therapy in correcting chronic hypoxaemia and reducing pulmonary vascular resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeferring oxygen therapy until PaO2 falls below 45 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as this patient already meets established criteria for long-term oxygen therapy. The threshold of 55 mmHg (or 59 mmHg with complications) is evidence-based and delaying treatment could result in continued deterioration and missed opportunity for survival benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of compensated respiratory acidosis (elevated HCO3-) and signs of right heart failure further support the need for long-term oxygen therapy. When prescribing, it\u0027s important to educate the patient about fire safety, the importance of adherence to at least 15 hours daily use, and to arrange regular follow-up including annual arterial blood gas assessment to ensure ongoing eligibility and appropriate oxygen dosing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Long-term oxygen therapy is indicated in COPD when arterial PaO2 is \u226455 mmHg or \u226459 mmHg with complications such as pulmonary hypertension.","Oxygen flow should be titrated to achieve SpO2 88-92% or PaO2 \u226560 mmHg, starting at 1-2 L/min via nasal prongs.","Long-term oxygen therapy improves survival in COPD with severe hypoxaemia when used for at least 15 hours per day."],"references":["Lung Foundation Australia. COPD\u2011X Plan Handbook, Version 1. Melbourne: Lung Foundation Australia; 2024 Aug. Available from: https://lungfoundation.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/COPD-X_Handbook_Version1.pdf","COPD\u2011X Steering Committee. Hypoxaemia and pulmonary hypertension. In: COPD\u2011X Plan \u2013 Optimise function. Version current as of at least September 2024. Australia: Lung Foundation Australia \u0026 Thoracic Society of Australia and New Zealand. Available at: https://copdx.org.au/copd-x-plan/o-optimise-function/o8-hypoxaemia-and-pulmonary-hypertension/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89099"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22102"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89099"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-20T22:47:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-17T10:12:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15063"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106622"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","